This document describes the hardware environment, runtime configuration, random seed settings, and reporting protocol used for reproducing the main results of PoplarCrossOmics.

1. Hardware configuration

The main experiments reported in the manuscript were conducted on the following hardware:

- GPU: NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4090
- GPU memory: 24 GB VRAM
- CUDA: 12.8
- CPU: A standard multi-core x86_64 workstation/server CPU is sufficient for preprocessing and training orchestration
- System memory (recommended): at least 32 GB RAM

In our setting, GPU memory usage was well within the 24 GB capacity of the RTX 4090 for the full training procedure.

2. Training time

For the main experiment setting:

- Training epochs: 300
- Approximate wall-clock time: ~7 minutes on a single NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4090 (24 GB VRAM)

The exact runtime may vary depending on CPU speed, storage I/O, PyTorch/CUDA build, and background GPU load.

3. Random seeds and stochastic components

To improve reproducibility, the implementation fixes the random seeds for the major stochastic components used during training and data preparation.

 3.1 Fixed random seed

The default random seed is:

- seed = 42

This value is exposed in the training script as:


python run.py --gpu 0 --epochs 300 --lr 1e-3 --seed 42
